Anthony:

I fear that a lot of your concern over how well QS works in practice is 
due to inexperience on the part of many of the people who are members of 
this list.  I seldom have to give any thought to which TH sound to 
write.  And if I do occasionally hesitate, it is only for a moment.  I 
cam sure that the reason for occasional hesitation is that we all 
learned TO which doesn&#39;t make the distinction between the two letters.  
If children are taught QS in the future, they won&#39;t hesitate at all over 
which TH to use.  It certainly is not enough of a problem to justify 
throwing one of the TH letters out of the alphabet. 

Ooze and wool are quite distinct from each other and cause me no problem 
either.  My father pronounces Gary Cooper&#39;s name with the wool sound, 
and I use ooze.  We still manage to communicate.  I don&#39;t believe we 
should throw one sound out as that makes the alphabet less accurate in 
its representation of speech.  I especially like your terminology 
&quot;...provides the comfort of one letter per sound&quot; as if that is some 
sort of compromise.  Isn&#39;t that how an alphabet is supposed to work?   
If we throw ooze or wool out, then every time I come across that letter 
in a word, I have to decide which pronunciation it is supposed to have 
in this particular instance.

I understand that for fast reading, we want to limit spelling variants 
to a reasonable number.  But I still believe that the number of variants 
will be low enough that it will not cause a significant reading speed 
diminution, and I believe this is borne out by the experience of the 
early QS writers.  Moira could address that point as well.  Everyone 
doesn&#39;t have to spell every word the same.

If I can read &quot;why&quot; written without a wh sound as we now have in the QS 
News, I&#39;m sure a person who doesn&#39;t use wh can read why written with 
it.  Throwing out wh will just annoy the people to whom it is 
important.  Frankly, I don&#39;t think they would agree to it.  I know I won&#39;t.

For those who merge awe, on and ox or some subset thereof, let them 
spell all these words with on or however they want to.  It will look 
peculiar to me, but I can figure it out just as I&#39;m sure they will 
figure out what I am talking about. 

By the way, I also pronounce the &quot;l&quot; in the middle of &quot;palm&quot; and 
&quot;calm&quot;.  A &quot;pom&quot; is what I call my dog (Pomeranian).

Loch and Llan don&#39;t bother me one way or the other.  They exist in the 
QS manual, but I&#39;ve never had the need for them.  They can sit there and 
not bother anybody.  If a font designer leaves them out of his font, the 
vast majority of people won&#39;t care.

Paige


